    "justification": "Two conjuncts. The second is a DISJUNCTION (InferenceOr) — the claim licenses iff EITHER the raw mean ordering OLD > YOUNG holds OR the chromosome-block bootstrap returns p < 0.001. The disjunction acknowledges that the surprising direction needs robust evidence: a small-block-bootstrap p without raw-direction agreement would be suspicious; raw-direction agreement without p < 0.001 would be vulnerable to spatial autocorrelation. EITHER alone is acceptable; both together is what we observe (p=0.002 and OLD > YOUNG). First InferenceOr exercised in the claim corpus.",
    "failure_mode": "If the OR conjunct collapsed (BOTH branches failed: OLD < YOUNG mean AND block-bootstrap p > 0.001), the surprise direction would dissolve and the gBGC framework would predict the standard (now wrong) direction."
  },
  "conclusion": {
    "assertion": "OLD crossover hotspots (top-quartile crossover rate AND top-quartile 241-way phyloP conservation) are MORE deformable on average than YOUNG hotspots (top-quartile crossover rate AND bottom-quartile phyloP), at Cohen's d = +1.73 with chromosome-block bootstrap p = 0.002. This contradicts the naive 'gBGC stiffens DNA over time' prediction; the material channel records gBGC's GC-enrichment scar (sibling claim recomb_a3_gbgc_age_gradient_gc) but not by direct stiffening — instead, the GC-enrichment is at sequence positions that increase rather than decrease deformability.",
    "formal": null,
